  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is generally considered a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This activity is illegal because it allows criminals to \"clean\" money derived from illegal activities, making it appear legitimate.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is a federal crime under the **Bank Secrecy Act** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- Significant fines (up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater).\n- Imprisonment for up to 20 years per violation.\n- Civil penalties and forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering scheme.\n\nAdditionally, many states have their own laws against money laundering, which can also result in felony charges, fines, and imprisonment. The severity of the penalties often depends on the amount of money laundered, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and whether the individual is a repeat offender.\n\nIt's important to note that even attempting to launder money or conspiring to do so can result in felony charges.",
